---
import Section from "~/components/Section.astro";
import Stage from "~/components/Stage.astro";

// Reuse the toy example from the previous page.
const cellsBefore: (number | null)[] = [
  3, 6, null, null,   // Segment 0 — this is the one that was just queried
  7, null, 4, null,
  null, 5, 0, null,
  null, 1, null, 2,
];
// After relocating segment 0: its two real values (3 at cell 0, 6 at cell 1)
// each move to a random empty cell outside segment 0. Segment 0's four cells
// all become ⊥. The two empty slots that receive values become real.
// Here: 3 → cell 5 (segment 1, position 1), 6 → cell 8 (segment 2, position 0).
const cellsAfter: (number | null)[] = [
  null, null, null, null, // Segment 0 — now all empty
  7, 3, 4, null,          // Segment 1: 3 landed at cell 5
  6, 5, 0, null,          // Segment 2: 6 landed at cell 8
  null, 1, null, 2,       // Segment 3 — untouched
];
// Cells that received a relocated value:
const landedCells = [5, 8];
const T = 4;
---

<Section id="harmonypir-permutation" num="06" title="HarmonyPIR — relocation and the permutation">
  <p>
    The previous page left a loose thread. The query into segment
    <code>s</code> revealed most of that segment to the server — every
    real DB index in it except the one at the target's slot, which got
    replaced by a random cell from outside. The target itself stays
    hidden behind the client's hint XOR, so a single request leaks
    nothing about what was asked for. The danger is reuse: if the client
    later needs to fetch another index whose original home is segment
    <code>s</code>, the protocol would have to use segment <code>s</code>
    again, and the two requests would look nearly identical — the same
    (T−1) real cells from segment <code>s</code>, just a different
    position swapped out for a different outside cell. Correlating the
    two lets the server reverse-engineer which position was "the
    replacement" each time, pinning down the permutation. So segment
    <code>s</code> has to retire after one use. But the DB indices it
    held still need to be reachable — they have to be re-homed into
    other segments.
  </p>
  <p>
    Concretely: the real values in segment <code>s</code> (two in our
    running example; in general up to <code>T</code>) each move to a
    fresh random empty cell somewhere else in the hint row, one at a
    time. Segment <code>s</code> becomes all <code>⊥</code>. The client
    updates its stored parities to match — each segment that received
    one of the moved values gets that entry XOR-ed into its parity. Once
    the bookkeeping is done, the hint table is back to the same shape
    it had before, only permuted differently and with fewer empty cells
    left over.
  </p>

  <Stage
    caption="After querying segment 0, its two real values scatter to random empty cells. Segment 0 is now all ⊥; two previously-empty cells elsewhere in the row now hold those values. Hint parities are updated accordingly."
    label="Segment relocation"
  >
    <svg viewBox="0 0 680 260" role="img"
      aria-label="Hint row before and after relocation. Segment 0's values move to random empty cells in other segments; segment 0 becomes all empty.">

      <defs>
        <marker id="rel-arr" viewBox="0 0 10 10" refX="8" refY="5"
          markerWidth="5" markerHeight="5" orient="auto">
          <path d="M 0 0 L 10 5 L 0 10 z" fill="#e8a33c"/>
        </marker>
      </defs>

      <!-- BEFORE -->
      <text x="20" y="22" font-size="11" font-weight="700" fill="var(--fg)">
        Before: query just happened on segment 0
      </text>
      {cellsBefore.map((v, i) => {
        const smallW = 34;
        const smallGap = 2;
        const x = 20 + i * (smallW + smallGap);
        const y = 32;
        const isReal = v !== null;
        const inSeg0 = i < T;
        return (
          <g>
            <rect x={x} y={y} width={smallW} height={26} rx="3"
              fill={inSeg0 && isReal ? "#e8a33c"
                : isReal ? "var(--accent-bg)"
                : "var(--bg-elev-2)"}
              stroke={inSeg0 && isReal ? "#c98728"
                : isReal ? "var(--accent)"
                : "var(--border)"}/>
            <text x={x + smallW / 2} y={y + 17}
              text-anchor="middle" font-size="10"
              font-family="ui-monospace, monospace"
              fill={inSeg0 && isReal ? "#0a0b0f"
                : isReal ? "var(--accent)"
                : "var(--fg-dim)"}
              font-weight={inSeg0 && isReal ? "700" : "500"}>
              {isReal ? v : "⊥"}
            </text>
          </g>
        );
      })}
      {[1, 2, 3].map((k) => {
        const x = 20 + k * T * 36 - 1;
        return (
          <line x1={x} y1={28} x2={x} y2={62}
            stroke="var(--fg-muted)" stroke-width="1"/>
        );
      })}

      <!-- Arrows showing where each segment-0 value moves -->
      {[
        { from: 0, to: 5 }, // 3 → cell 5
        { from: 1, to: 8 }, // 6 → cell 8
      ].map(({ from, to }) => {
        const fx = 20 + from * 36 + 17;
        const tx = 20 + to * 36 + 17;
        const yTop = 62;
        const yBot = 138;
        return (
          <path
            d={`M ${fx} ${yTop} C ${fx} ${yTop + 30}, ${tx} ${yBot - 30}, ${tx} ${yBot}`}
            stroke="#e8a33c" stroke-width="1" fill="none"
            stroke-dasharray="3 3" opacity="0.6" marker-end="url(#rel-arr)"/>
        );
      })}

      <!-- AFTER -->
      <text x="20" y="130" font-size="11" font-weight="700" fill="var(--fg)">
        After: segment 0 is empty, values scattered into previously-⊥ cells
      </text>
      {cellsAfter.map((v, i) => {
        const smallW = 34;
        const smallGap = 2;
        const x = 20 + i * (smallW + smallGap);
        const y = 140;
        const isReal = v !== null;
        // Highlight the cells that received a relocated value.
        const landedIn = landedCells.includes(i);
        return (
          <g>
            <rect x={x} y={y} width={smallW} height={26} rx="3"
              fill={landedIn ? "#e8a33c"
                : isReal ? "var(--accent-bg)"
                : "var(--bg-elev-2)"}
              stroke={landedIn ? "#c98728"
                : isReal ? "var(--accent)"
                : "var(--border)"}/>
            <text x={x + smallW / 2} y={y + 17}
              text-anchor="middle" font-size="10"
              font-family="ui-monospace, monospace"
              fill={landedIn ? "#0a0b0f"
                : isReal ? "var(--accent)"
                : "var(--fg-dim)"}
              font-weight={landedIn ? "700" : "500"}>
              {isReal ? v : "⊥"}
            </text>
          </g>
        );
      })}
      {[1, 2, 3].map((k) => {
        const x = 20 + k * T * 36 - 1;
        return (
          <line x1={x} y1={136} x2={x} y2={170}
            stroke="var(--fg-muted)" stroke-width="1"/>
        );
      })}

      <!-- Budget / exhaustion indicator -->
      <text x="20" y="200" font-size="10" font-weight="700" fill="var(--fg)">
        Empty-cell budget
      </text>
      <g transform="translate(20,210)">
        <rect width="640" height="12" rx="2" fill="var(--bg-elev-2)" stroke="var(--border)"/>
        <rect width="480" height="12" rx="2" fill="var(--ok)" opacity="0.65"/>
        <rect x="480" width="160" height="12" rx="2" fill="#e14a5a" opacity="0.35"/>
      </g>
      <text x="20" y="240" font-size="9" class="svg-label" fill="var(--fg-muted)" font-style="italic">
        Each query consumes T of the empty cells in the row. After ~M/2 queries
        they're all used up, and the offline phase has to run again against a
        fresh permutation.
      </text>
    </svg>
  </Stage>

  <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">The permutation backend</h3>
  <p>
    A design choice in HarmonyPIR is to use <em>one</em> random
    permutation of size <code>2N</code> for the entire hint row, rather
    than separate per-partition shuffles. This lets the scheme plug in
    any off-the-shelf PRP large enough to cover the domain.
  </p>

  <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">What BitcoinPIR actually wires in</h3>
  <p>
    The <code>harmonypir</code> crate keeps the permutation behind a
    <code>Prp</code> trait and ships two backends, each with a different
    trade. The BitcoinPIR SDK exposes the choice as a runtime flag,
    with <strong>FastPRP</strong> the production default.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>HMR12.</strong> An AES-based card-shuffle PRP with a
      security reduction to AES; BitcoinPIR uses a tweaked variant
      (Algorithm 5 in the HarmonyPIR paper) that cuts AES calls by ~4×
      per evaluation via phase grouping. Pure AES, no extra dependencies,
      compiles cleanly to WASM. ~6 µs/op native, ~14 µs/op in a browser.
      Works at any database size. Based on Hoang, Morris &amp; Rogaway,
      <a href="https://eprint.iacr.org/2012/338" target="_blank"
        rel="noopener"><em>An Enciphering Scheme Based on a Card
        Shuffle</em></a> (CRYPTO 2012) — hence the shorthand
      <strong>HMR12</strong>.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>FastPRP</strong> (default). A small-domain PRP that
      builds a permutation cache (~60 ms at <code>N</code> ≈ 6M) and
      answers subsequent evaluations in <code>O(√N log N)</code>; ideal
      for the server's one-off offline hint generation over many groups
      at once. Implements Stefanov &amp; Shi,
      <a href="https://eprint.iacr.org/2012/254" target="_blank"
        rel="noopener"><em>FastPRP: Fast Pseudo-Random Permutations for
        Small Domains</em></a> (ePrint 2012/254).
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p style="font-size: 0.92rem; color: var(--fg-muted);">
    Earlier versions of the SDK also shipped an <strong>ALF</strong>
    backend (Wang, Maximov &amp; Johansson,
    <a href="https://eprint.iacr.org/2025/2148" target="_blank"
      rel="noopener"><em>Introducing the ALF family</em></a>, ePrint
    2025/2148). ALF was retired in May 2026 because its implementation
    panicked on domains smaller than 2<sup>16</sup>, which the
    sibling-Merkle hint tables routinely hit. FastPRP is now the
    default; HMR12 remains as a pure-AES alternative.
  </p>
  <p>
    The BitcoinPIR deployment runs HarmonyPIR <em>per cuckoo-hash group</em>:
    75 INDEX groups plus 80 CHUNK groups in the current parameters, each
    with its own hint row and its own PRP instance, all under a single
    master client key. The group structure comes from the batch-code layer
    two sections from now — same pattern for every backend, so we'll cover
    it once there.
  </p>
</Section>
